All of the common distributions are available in R, and for every
distribution R can calculate various properties. There is a root name
for each distribution (e.g `norm` for the normal distribution) and the
following prefixes to the name of the distribution to do the following:

`d` to generate the probability mass or density function\
Example: `dnorm(x,mean,sd)`

`p` to generate the probability [\\(P(X \\le x)\\)]{.math} (the cdf)\
Example: `pnorm(q,mean,sd)`

`q` to generate the quantile [\\(P(X \\le x) \> q\\)]{.math} (inverse
cdf)\
Example: `qnorm(p,mean,sd)`

`r` to generate a random variable having the specified distribution\
Example: `rnorm(n,mean,sd)`

#### Using `d` functions

The `d` functions find the pmf for discrete distributions and the pdf
for continuous distributions, namely returning the probability density
for a given value of random variable X, [\\(P(X=x)\\)]{.math}. For a
given range of values [\\(x\_1,\...,x\_n\\)]{.math}, we can find the
density and plot the density function. For example, to generate the
standard normal pdf, define some observations x, and apply `dnorm` with
[\\(\\mu=0\\)]{.math} and [\\(\\sigma=1\\)]{.math} (note these are the
default values of dnorm):

```r
x <- seq(-3,3,0.01)
# Plot Normal Distribution
plot(x=x, y=dnorm(x, mean=0, sd=1), type='l')
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}
Let's look at the t distribution with different degrees of freedom and
compare it to the standard normal distribution

```r
# provide same x observations as above
x <- seq(-3,3,0.01)
# try different degrees of freedom
df <- c(1, 3, 5, 50)
# set up colours and labels for the functions and plot legend
colors <- c("red", "blue", "darkgreen", "gold", "black")
labels <- c("df=1", "df=3", "df=5", "df=50", "standard normal")
# plot Z first
plot(x, dnorm(x), type="l", lty=2, xlab="x value",
     ylab="Density", main="Comparison of t Distributions")
# add lines representing t-distribution
for (i in 1:4){
  lines(x, dt(x,df[i]), lwd=2, col=colors[i])
}
# add legend
legend("topright", title="t-Distribution",
       labels, lwd=2, lty=c(1, 1, 1, 1, 2), col=colors)
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

We see how when df-\>[\\(\\infty\\)]{.math}, t converges to the standard
normal distribution.

For a binomial random variable, suppose you take a multiple choice exam
with 10 questions. Each question has 5 possible answers, with only one
being correct. You didn't study so guess the answers. What is the
probability of getting exactly 6 correct Pr(X=6)?

```r
dbinom(6,size=10,prob=1/5)
```

    [1] 0.005505024

The distribution of all possible results on the test

```r
y<-dbinom(0:10,size=10,prob=1/5)
barplot(y,space=0,names.arg=c(0:10))
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

#### Using `p` functions

The `p` functions find [\\(F(x) = P(X \\le x)\\)]{.math}, thus providing
the probability for the "lower tail" of the distribution. Basically,
this function will return the probability for which a given number or a
vector of numbers is less than or equal to a value. Should we wish to
find the probability for the "upper tail", we can choose the option
`lower=FALSE` in any of the distribution functions. For example, an
application of the Poisson distribution:\
Suppose there are on average 10 asthmatic patients that come to a
particular health clinic on a given day. What is the probability that
only 4 will come to the clinic today?

```r
ppois(4,lambda=10)
```

    [1] 0.02925269

This is the probability that 4 or fewer will come to the clinic today.
The probability of 5 or more coming to the clinic will be

```r
ppois(4,lambda=10, lower=FALSE)
```

    [1] 0.9707473

An example using the normal distribution, suppose we have data between
-2 and 2 and we wish to find the probabilities of their values given
that they come from a normal population with mean -1 and standard
deviation 1. We plot the probabilities against each value of our random
variable X.

```r
x <- seq(-2,2,by=0.1)
y <- pnorm(x,mean=-1,sd=1)
plot(x,y, ylab="P(X<=x)",xlab="x")
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

#### Using `q` functions

The `q` functions are the inverse of the `p` functions, meaning that for
a given probability the quantile (percentile) value q for the cumulative
distribution will be returned [\\(P(X \\le x) \> q\\)]{.math}. For
instance, for a standard normal distribution the `qnorm` function for
p=0.95 will return the z-score 1.64.

```r
qnorm(0.95,mean=0,sd=1)
```

    [1] 1.644854

Another example: find the 99th percentile of the [\\(\\chi\^2\\)]{.math}
distribution with 6 degrees of freedom.

```r
qchisq(0.99,6)
```

    [1] 16.81189

#### Using `r` functions

The `r` functions generate a random sample of a specified size from the
distribution of choice.\
Let's generate 7 observations from a uniform distribution on the
interval \[1,5\] and sort it in ascending order

```r
x<-runif(7,1,5)
sort(x)
```

    [1] 1.292336 1.903070 2.845815 3.267600 4.196206 4.705819 4.725922

#### Additional uses of the functions

Suppose we know IQ scores are normally distributed with a mean of 100
and a standard deviation of 15. What proportion of children are expected
to have an IQ between 80 and 120? This is an application of `pnorm`, and
if we wish to plot the area under the normal distribution that
corresponds to this area, we additionally apply `dnorm`.

```r
# set up necessary parameters
mean=100
sd=15
lb=80
ub=120
# create vector of x's: 100 observations around the given mean and sd
x <- seq(-4,4,length=100)*sd + mean
# find probabilities for these values given the distribution parameters
hx <- dnorm(x,mean,sd)
# plot
plot(x, hx, type="n", xlab="IQ Values", ylab="", main="Normal Distribution", axes=FALSE)
# add lines at the upper and lower bounds
i <- x >= lb & x <= ub
lines(x, hx)
# create polygon for shading area of distribution
polygon(c(lb,x[i],ub), c(0,hx[i],0), col="lightblue") 
area <- pnorm(ub, mean, sd) - pnorm(lb, mean, sd)
# add title and axis labels
mtext(paste("P(",lb,"< IQ <",ub,")=",signif(area, digits=3)),3)
axis(1, at=seq(40, 160, 20), pos=0)
```
